            <div type="translation">
                <p>Ὁ ἅγιος Γεώργιος. / Σφραγὶς Θεοδώρου τοῦ Λουλάκη.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Saint George. / Seal of Theodore Loulakes.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">Heiliger Georg. / Siegel des Theodoros Lulakes</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p>The owner of the seal, Theodore Loulakes, is known from the seals he left.[1] He is attested on three more specimina, all of which seem to be parallels of our seal: two of them belong to the collection of Dumbarton Oaks,[2] one to the Hermitage State Museum in St. Petersburg.[3] One of the three specimina was published by A.-K. Wassiliou within the context of previously unattested family names on Byzantine seals.[4]</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="footnotes">
                  <p xml:id="footnote-1">
                      [1]. See <bibl><ptr target="PBW"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.2774/view">Theodoros no. 20351</ref></citedRange></bibl>.
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-2">
                      <!-- Angabe "[accessed December 21, 2020]" auch angeben?-->
                      [2]. Dumbarton Oaks BZS.1958.106.2774 (published in the <bibl><ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.2774/view">BZS.1958.106.2774</ref></citedRange></bibl>) and BZS.1958.106.5672 (<bibl><ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>, <citedRange unit="entry"><ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.5672">BZS.1958.106.5672</ref></citedRange></bibl>).
                  </p>
                  <p xml:id="footnote-3">
                      [3]. State Hermitage Museum M-10774.
                  </p>
                <p xml:id="footnote-4">
                    [4]. See <bibl><ptr target="Wassiliou2006"/>, p. <citedRange unit="page">77</citedRange>, no. <citedRange unit="entry">11</citedRange></bibl>. The publication does not specify which of the three seals the edition refers to. However, the printed photograph seems to match Dumbarton Oaks BZS.1958.106.5672. Wassiliou argues that the family name Loulakes might stem from the Greek word Λουλάκιον (arab. līlak), referring to a plant from which the homonymous purple dye is produced (<bibl><ptr target="Wassiliou2006"/>, n. <citedRange unit="page">35</citedRange></bibl>).
                </p>
              </div>
